const e=JSON.parse('[{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","type":"title"},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"saddle-world-hex-grid","anchor":"","type":"content","content":"Hexagonal grid math, layout conversion, iterators, field of view, pathfinding, dense storage, and grid topology helpers for Bevy. The crate stays math-first: coordinate conversion, neighbors, distance, rings, spirals, FOV, pathfinding, and movement budgets work in ordinary Rust code without starting a Bevy app. The plugin is optional and only owns the runtime-facing debug overlay surface."},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Why this crate exists","anchor":"#why-this-crate-exists","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Why this crate exists","anchor":"#why-this-crate-exists","type":"content","content":"saddle-world-hex-grid is meant to be a reusable shared module for: - tactics and roguelike boards - 4X or strategy overlays - procgen and map editors - district or influence radius tools - hybrid 2D or 3D games that need world-space picking over a hex lattice - turn-based games needing movement ranges, attack ranges, and field of view It borrows concepts from Red Blob Games\' hex grid guides, hexx, and Catlike Coding\'s hex map tutorials, but reimplements the coordinate and traversal code directly to keep the API small, project-agnostic, and Bevy-friendly."},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Quick start","anchor":"#quick-start","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Public API","anchor":"#public-api","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Coordinate types","anchor":"#coordinate-types","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Coordinate types","anchor":"#coordinate-types","type":"content","content":"- AxialHex: ergonomic default coordinate type for gameplay and storage. - CubeHex: fully explicit cube coordinates with q + r + s == 0 invariant checks. - OffsetHex: odd-r / even-r / odd-q / even-q adapter for rectangular storage or tilemap interop. - DoubledHex: double-width / double-height adapter for dense rectangular projections and editor-style indexing. - FractionalHex: world-picking and interpolation helper with robust rounding back to AxialHex. Mode-dependent adapters stay explicit on purpose: - axial.tooffset(mode) and offset.toaxial(mode) - axial.todoubled(mode) and doubled.toaxial(mode) There is no blanket From<DoubledHex> conversion because doubled coordinates are ambiguous without their projection mode."},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Layout and orientation","anchor":"#layout-and-orientation","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Layout and orientation","anchor":"#layout-and-orientation","type":"content","content":"- HexOrientation::{FlatTop, PointyTop} - HexLayout - hextoworld - worldtohex - worldtofractional - corners - edgemidpoints - rectsize Orientation is always explicit in world-space conversion. The same AxialHex resolves to different world positions depending on the selected layout."},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Directions and local steps","anchor":"#directions-and-local-steps","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Directions and local steps","anchor":"#directions-and-local-steps","type":"content","content":"- HexDirection — 6 face-adjacent directions with rotation, negation, angle(), unitvector(), vertexdirections(), from_angle() - HexDiagonalDirection — 6 diagonal directions with rotation, opposite, index"},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Distance operations","anchor":"#distance-operations","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Distance operations","anchor":"#distance-operations","type":"content","content":"- distanceto(other) — Manhattan (hex) distance - distancesqto(other) — squared Euclidean distance (no sqrt, useful for comparisons) - euclideandistance_to(other) — Euclidean distance between hex centers"},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Iterators and shape helpers","anchor":"#iterators-and-shape-helpers","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Iterators and shape helpers","anchor":"#iterators-and-shape-helpers","type":"content","content":"- lineto - range / hexagon - ring - spiral - parallelogram - offsetrectangle - doubled_rectangle - triangle - wedge The iterator-based API keeps most shape queries allocation-light. Collect into a Vec only when you need ownership."},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Field of view","anchor":"#field-of-view","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Field of view","anchor":"#field-of-view","type":"content","content":"- rangefov(origin, range, isblocking) — 360-degree FOV using raycasting to the perimeter ring - directionalfov(origin, range, direction, isblocking) — 120-degree directional cone FOV - DiagonalWay — result type for diagonal direction queries FOV is caller-owned: provide a closure that decides which hexes block line of sight. Blocking hexes are included in the result (you can see a wall, but not past it)."},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Pathfinding and movement range","anchor":"#pathfinding-and-movement-range","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Pathfinding and movement range","anchor":"#pathfinding-and-movement-range","type":"content","content":"- astar(start, goal, edgecost) - reachablewithin(start, budget, edgecost) - HexPath - HexReachability Traversal is storage-agnostic. The caller owns map storage and terrain rules. The crate only asks for an edge-cost closure: - return None to block a move - return Some(cost) for a legal move - use larger costs for terrain, rivers, roads, or one-way rules This separation keeps the core reusable for HashMap, arrays, ECS-backed worlds, editor tools, or generated maps."},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Bounds","anchor":"#bounds","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Bounds","anchor":"#bounds","type":"content","content":"- HexBounds — circular bounds with contains, hex_count, iter, intersects, wrap"},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Dense storage","anchor":"#dense-storage","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Dense storage","anchor":"#dense-storage","type":"content","content":"- HexagonalMap<T> — O(1) indexed dense storage over a hexagonal region, backed by a flat Vec"},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Grid topology","anchor":"#grid-topology","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Grid topology","anchor":"#grid-topology","type":"content","content":"- GridEdge — canonical edge between two adjacent hexes, with hexes() and vertices() - GridVertex — canonical vertex shared by three hexes, with hexes() and edges() Useful for strategy/building games that need to reason about hex borders and corners (rivers along edges, cities at vertices, etc.)."},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Plugin and debug surface","anchor":"#plugin-and-debug-surface","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Plugin and debug surface","anchor":"#plugin-and-debug-surface","type":"content","content":"The plugin is intentionally thin: - HexGridPlugin - HexGridSystems::{SyncDebug, DrawDebug} - HexGridDebugSettings - HexDebugOverlay - HexGridDebugGizmos Use the plugin when you want runtime gizmo overlays for centers, outlines, highlighted cells, FOV regions, or path previews. Skip it entirely if you only need math and traversal. The plugin initializes its own HexGridDebugGizmos group, so HexDebugOverlay works out of the box once the plugin is added and debug drawing is enabled. The plugin uses injectable schedules:"},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Coordinate systems","anchor":"#coordinate-systems","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Coordinate systems","anchor":"#coordinate-systems","type":"content","content":"First-class: - AxialHex - CubeHex Adapters: - OffsetHex - DoubledHex AxialHex is the main public workhorse because it is compact, readable, and cheap to convert. CubeHex stays first-class because distance, interpolation, and invariant-sensitive algorithms are easier to reason about in cube space. Offset and doubled forms exist for interoperability and storage layout, not as the core algorithm surface."},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Examples","anchor":"#examples","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Examples","anchor":"#examples","type":"content","content":"Every shipped example includes a live saddle-pane control so layout changes and parameters can be inspected interactively. Run them with:"},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Dependency philosophy","anchor":"#dependency-philosophy","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"saddle-world-hex-grid","slug":"/","heading":"Dependency philosophy","anchor":"#dependency-philosophy","type":"content","content":"Runtime dependencies stay minimal: - bevy = \\"0.18\\" only No project-specific crates, no game_core, and no wrapper dependency on hexx. The crate owns its math, traversal, and debug code directly."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","type":"title"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Design goals","anchor":"#design-goals","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Design goals","anchor":"#design-goals","type":"content","content":"saddle-world-hex-grid exists to provide durable hex-grid primitives that work in pure Rust first and Bevy second. The design priorities are: 1. keep coordinate math independent from ECS and rendering 2. make world-space conversion explicit about orientation and size 3. keep traversal generic over caller-owned storage and terrain policy 4. offer an optional Bevy plugin for debug overlays without forcing a runtime model"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Coordinate model choices","anchor":"#coordinate-model-choices","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"First-class coordinate systems","anchor":"#first-class-coordinate-systems","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"First-class coordinate systems","anchor":"#first-class-coordinate-systems","type":"content","content":"- AxialHex - CubeHex AxialHex is the ergonomic center of the API. It stores only q and r, derives s on demand, and keeps gameplay code readable. CubeHex stays first-class because some invariants are clearer in cube space: - exact q + r + s == 0 validation - interpolation and rounding - rotation and reflection - distance reasoning The crate exposes both because forcing everything into axial coordinates tends to hide the cube invariant, while forcing everything into cube coordinates makes common gameplay code heavier than needed."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Adapter coordinate systems","anchor":"#adapter-coordinate-systems","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Adapter coordinate systems","anchor":"#adapter-coordinate-systems","type":"content","content":"- OffsetHex - DoubledHex These are adapter types for storage and interoperability: - OffsetHex maps cleanly to odd or even row and column layouts used by editors and tilemap tools. - DoubledHex supports dense rectangular indexing patterns without making offset parity part of every algorithm. Algorithms operate on AxialHex and CubeHex, then convert at the boundaries. This keeps the implementation smaller and avoids subtle parity bugs leaking into pathfinding or line drawing. Adapter conversions remain explicit. In particular, DoubledHex does not implement a blanket Into<AxialHex> because the same doubled pair can only be interpreted correctly once the caller provides DoubledHexMode."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Fractional coordinates","anchor":"#fractional-coordinates","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Fractional coordinates","anchor":"#fractional-coordinates","type":"content","content":"FractionalHex is kept explicit instead of hidden inside HexLayout. It exists for: - robust world-to-hex rounding - interpolation for line drawing - debug and picking workflows where the intermediate fractional result matters The rounding code follows the standard cube-rounding approach popularized by Red Blob Games: round each cube axis, then repair the axis with the largest rounding error to re-enforce the cube invariant."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Layout architecture","anchor":"#layout-architecture","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Layout architecture","anchor":"#layout-architecture","type":"content","content":"HexLayout owns world-space conversion: - orientation - hex size - origin This is intentionally separate from coordinate storage. A grid coordinate should not imply how it is rendered. The layout API exposes: - center conversion: hextoworld - inverse conversion: worldtohex - intermediate conversion: worldtofractional - geometry helpers: corners, edgemidpoints, rectsize Flat-top and pointy-top are both first-class because users often need both in the same workspace: gameplay, editors, debug tools, or imported content may disagree on orientation."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Traversal architecture","anchor":"#traversal-architecture","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Traversal architecture","anchor":"#traversal-architecture","type":"content","content":"Traversal APIs are graph-oriented instead of map-container-oriented."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"A*","anchor":"#a","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"A*","anchor":"#a","type":"content","content":"astar(start, goal, edgecost) asks the caller for the cost of moving from one hex to another. The closure decides: - which edges are blocked - whether cost is symmetric or directed - whether terrain is weighted - whether world bounds or chunk streaming allow the move The function returns Option<HexPath> and keeps its internal node representation private so the search implementation can change later without breaking consumers."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Reachability","anchor":"#reachability","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Reachability","anchor":"#reachability","type":"content","content":"reachablewithin(start, budget, edgecost) is a budget-limited Dijkstra search. It returns HexReachability, which stores: - per-cell cost - predecessor links for path reconstruction back to the origin This covers common tactical and builder workflows: - movement previews - service or influence ranges - flood fill over weighted terrain - previewing the cheapest route to any reachable target"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Shape and iterator architecture","anchor":"#shape-and-iterator-architecture","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Shape and iterator architecture","anchor":"#shape-and-iterator-architecture","type":"content","content":"Most geometry helpers are iterators rather than allocation-heavy constructors. Current iterator families: - lines - filled ranges - exact rings - spirals - parallelograms - offset-projected rectangles - doubled-projected rectangles - triangles - wedges (arc sectors between two directions) The crate still offers convenience constructors such as hexagon(...), but the iterator-first design keeps hot paths lighter and leaves allocation choices to the caller."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Field of view architecture","anchor":"#field-of-view-architecture","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Field of view architecture","anchor":"#field-of-view-architecture","type":"content","content":"The crate provides two FOV functions: rangefov (360-degree) and directionalfov (120-degree cone)."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Algorithm","anchor":"#algorithm","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Algorithm","anchor":"#algorithm","type":"content","content":"Both use raycasting from the origin to the perimeter ring at the given range: 1. Enumerate every hex on the ring at distance range from the origin 2. For each perimeter hex, cast a line (using line_to) from origin to that hex 3. Walk the line; if a hex is blocking, include it but stop the ray This is a simple, predictable approach that handles concave obstacles well. The trade-off is that perimeter size grows linearly with range, so very large ranges cast many rays. For typical game ranges (1–10), this is negligible."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Directional FOV","anchor":"#directional-fov","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Directional FOV","anchor":"#directional-fov","type":"content","content":"directionalfov filters the perimeter ring to only include hexes within the 120-degree cone facing the given direction. It uses diagonalway to classify each perimeter hex into a diagonal sector and only casts rays into the matching sector."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Closure ownership","anchor":"#closure-ownership","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Closure ownership","anchor":"#closure-ownership","type":"content","content":"Like pathfinding, FOV is caller-owned: the is_blocking closure decides which hexes block line of sight. This keeps the FOV independent of any specific map storage."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Bounds architecture","anchor":"#bounds-architecture","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Bounds architecture","anchor":"#bounds-architecture","type":"content","content":"HexBounds is a lightweight circular bounds type (center + radius) for quick containment checks, iteration, and overlap tests without allocating a set. It also supports wrap for toroidal/repeating maps."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Dense storage architecture","anchor":"#dense-storage-architecture","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Dense storage architecture","anchor":"#dense-storage-architecture","type":"content","content":"HexagonalMap<T> provides O(1) indexed storage over a hexagonal region. Internally it uses a flat Vec<T> with row-by-row indexing plus a precomputed row-start table, so any (q, r) lookup becomes: 1. translate into local coordinates around the map center 2. compute the row index 3. jump to the row start 4. offset within that row This keeps random access constant-time while preserving a cache-friendly row-major iteration order."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Grid topology architecture","anchor":"#grid-topology-architecture","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Grid topology architecture","anchor":"#grid-topology-architecture","type":"content","content":"GridEdge and GridVertex represent the edges and vertices of the hex grid in canonical form. Canonical form ensures that two constructions of the same geometric feature (from different hexes) always produce the same struct value, enabling use as HashMap keys or in sets. - GridEdge picks the lexicographically smaller hex and adjusts the direction accordingly - GridVertex picks the lexicographically smallest of the three hexes sharing the vertex These types are useful for strategy and building games that need to reason about hex borders (rivers, walls, roads) and corners (cities, intersections)."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Plugin and debug architecture","anchor":"#plugin-and-debug-architecture","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Plugin and debug architecture","anchor":"#plugin-and-debug-architecture","type":"content","content":"The plugin is intentionally thin and optional."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"What the plugin owns","anchor":"#what-the-plugin-owns","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"What the plugin owns","anchor":"#what-the-plugin-owns","type":"content","content":"- runtime activation and deactivation through injectable schedules - public HexGridSystems - optional gizmo debug rendering through HexDebugOverlay - reflective registration of the public runtime-facing types - initialization of the crate\'s own gizmo config group"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"What the plugin does not own","anchor":"#what-the-plugin-does-not-own","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"What the plugin does not own","anchor":"#what-the-plugin-does-not-own","type":"content","content":"- map storage - picking - pathfinding state - gameplay rules - content-specific components HexDebugOverlay is the main runtime integration point. The overlay component stores authored data: - layout - cells - highlighted cells - path cells - FOV cells - colors The runtime system caches corner and path geometry into an internal component, then draws with bevygizmos if the user has initialized the gizmo group. This keeps the public overlay surface simple while avoiding recomputing corners every frame for unchanged overlays. drawcoord_labels remains on HexGridDebugSettings as a forward-looking toggle, but the current runtime is intentionally gizmo-only. Label rendering would require an additional text-backed runtime surface, so the flag is currently a documented no-op rather than a half-implemented feature."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Performance notes","anchor":"#performance-notes","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Complexity","anchor":"#complexity","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Complexity","anchor":"#complexity","type":"content","content":"- distanceto: O(1) - neighbor lookup: O(1) - line, ring, range, spiral: proportional to the number of returned cells - astar: O(E log V) in the explored frontier - reachable_within: O(E log V) in the explored frontier"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Current tradeoffs","anchor":"#current-tradeoffs","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Current tradeoffs","anchor":"#current-tradeoffs","type":"content","content":"- HashMap and BinaryHeap are used from the standard library for the initial implementation. - HexagonalMap iteration streams coordinates directly from row-major storage order instead of allocating temporary coordinate lists. - Search internals are private so the crate can later switch to denser storage, reusable buffers, or bucketed queues without a public API break. - Shape APIs favor iterators, but some runtime overlay paths still collect into Vecs because debug rendering wants owned geometry snapshots."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Intentional omissions","anchor":"#intentional-omissions","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Intentional omissions","anchor":"#intentional-omissions","type":"content","content":"The crate does not yet include: - chunked search acceleration - wraparound-aware heuristics - specialized storage backends - cached neighbor tables These are valid future additions, but they are not necessary for a stable 0.1.0 shared-crate surface."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Borrowed ideas and rejected scope","anchor":"#borrowed-ideas-and-rejected-scope","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Architecture","slug":"/docs/architecture/","heading":"Borrowed ideas and rejected scope","anchor":"#borrowed-ideas-and-rejected-scope","type":"content","content":"Borrowed ideas: - Red Blob Games: coordinate systems, rounding, lines, rings, spirals, world-layout framing - hexx: broad shape coverage, movement-field framing, and the reminder that storage should stay caller-owned - Catlike Coding: practical weighted pathfinding concerns and large-map thinking Rejected for now: - wraparound maps (beyond the simple HexBounds::wrap) - chunk coordinates - mesh generation helpers beyond corners and edge midpoints - a built-in ECS tile map or world representation Those features are useful, but shipping them now would either bloat the surface area or force content assumptions into what should stay a general-purpose shared math and traversal crate."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","type":"title"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexOrientation`","anchor":"#hexorientation","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexOrientation`","anchor":"#hexorientation","type":"content","content":"Controls how hexes are projected into world space."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Variants","anchor":"#variants","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Variants","anchor":"#variants","type":"content","content":"- FlatTop - PointyTop"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Implications","anchor":"#implications","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Implications","anchor":"#implications","type":"content","content":"- FlatTop places horizontal top and bottom edges on each hex. - PointyTop places a single corner at the top and bottom. - Orientation changes both the center-position formula and the corner-angle basis. Never mix an orientation with a layout authored for the other one."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexLayout`","anchor":"#hexlayout","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexLayout`","anchor":"#hexlayout","type":"content","content":"World-space conversion settings."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields","type":"content","content":"- orientation: HexOrientation - origin: Vec2 - hex_size: Vec2"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Defaults","anchor":"#defaults","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Defaults","anchor":"#defaults","type":"content","content":"- orientation = HexOrientation::FlatTop - origin = Vec2::ZERO - hex_size = Vec2::splat(1.0)"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Constructors and builders","anchor":"#constructors-and-builders","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Constructors and builders","anchor":"#constructors-and-builders","type":"content","content":"- HexLayout::flat() - HexLayout::pointy() - withorigin(Vec2) - withhexsize(Vec2) - withuniform_size(f32)"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Valid ranges and guidance","anchor":"#valid-ranges-and-guidance","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Valid ranges and guidance","anchor":"#valid-ranges-and-guidance","type":"content","content":"- hexsize.x > 0.0 - hexsize.y > 0.0 - use withuniformsize unless you intentionally want stretched hexes - keep origin in the same world space as the camera and gameplay systems that will use worldtohex"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Main methods","anchor":"#main-methods","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Main methods","anchor":"#main-methods","type":"content","content":"- hextoworld(AxialHex) -> Vec2 - worldtohex(Vec2) -> AxialHex - worldtofractional(Vec2) -> FractionalHex - corners(AxialHex) -> [Vec2; 6] - edgemidpoints(AxialHex) -> [Vec2; 6] - rectsize() -> Vec2"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`OffsetHexMode`","anchor":"#offsethexmode","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`OffsetHexMode`","anchor":"#offsethexmode","type":"content","content":"Selects the parity rule used by OffsetHex."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Variants","anchor":"#variants-1","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Variants","anchor":"#variants-1","type":"content","content":"- OddColumns - EvenColumns - OddRows - EvenRows"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Use cases","anchor":"#use-cases","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Use cases","anchor":"#use-cases","type":"content","content":"- OddColumns / EvenColumns: column-based offset storage - OddRows / EvenRows: row-based offset storage Pick the mode that matches the external editor, tilemap, or file format you need to interoperate with."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`DoubledHexMode`","anchor":"#doubledhexmode","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`DoubledHexMode`","anchor":"#doubledhexmode","type":"content","content":"Selects the doubled-coordinate projection used by DoubledHex."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Variants","anchor":"#variants-2","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Variants","anchor":"#variants-2","type":"content","content":"- DoubleWidth - DoubleHeight"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Use cases","anchor":"#use-cases-1","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Use cases","anchor":"#use-cases-1","type":"content","content":"- DoubleWidth: doubled columns, useful when a wide rectangular projection is more convenient - DoubleHeight: doubled rows, useful when height-major indexing fits better"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexGridDebugSettings`","anchor":"#hexgriddebugsettings","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexGridDebugSettings`","anchor":"#hexgriddebugsettings","type":"content","content":"Runtime debug resource used by the plugin."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields-1","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields-1","type":"content","content":"- enabled: bool - drawcenters: bool - drawcelloutlines: bool - drawpathlines: bool - drawcoordlabels: bool - centerradius: f32"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Defaults","anchor":"#defaults-1","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Defaults","anchor":"#defaults-1","type":"content","content":"- enabled = false - drawcenters = true - drawcelloutlines = true - drawpathlines = true - drawcoordlabels = false - centerradius = 6.0"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Valid ranges and guidance","anchor":"#valid-ranges-and-guidance-1","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Valid ranges and guidance","anchor":"#valid-ranges-and-guidance-1","type":"content","content":"- centerradius > 0.0 - use a radius smaller than the visual hex radius if you want the markers to stay inside the cell - if you only want path previews, disable center and outline drawing to reduce gizmo clutter - drawcoord_labels is reserved for future text rendering; the current gizmo-only debug runtime does not use it yet"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Example","anchor":"#example","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexDebugOverlay`","anchor":"#hexdebugoverlay","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexDebugOverlay`","anchor":"#hexdebugoverlay","type":"content","content":"Per-overlay component consumed by the debug runtime."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields-2","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields-2","type":"content","content":"- layout: HexLayout - cells: Vec<AxialHex> - highlighted: Vec<AxialHex> - path: Vec<AxialHex> - fovcells: Vec<AxialHex> - cellcolor: Color - highlightcolor: Color - pathcolor: Color - fov_color: Color"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Defaults","anchor":"#defaults-2","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Defaults","anchor":"#defaults-2","type":"content","content":"- empty cell, highlighted, path, and fov_cells vectors - semi-transparent blue cell color - amber highlight color - bright green path color - semi-transparent cyan fov color"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Guidance","anchor":"#guidance","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Guidance","anchor":"#guidance","type":"content","content":"- cells defines which hexes get center and outline rendering - highlighted is best for rings, selected cells, or transient focus regions - path is rendered as center-to-center line segments in order - fovcells renders FOV-visible hexes as colored outlines; populate from rangefov or directional_fov - use separate overlay entities when you want different color layers or update frequencies"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexGridPlugin`","anchor":"#hexgridplugin","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexGridPlugin`","anchor":"#hexgridplugin","type":"content","content":"Optional runtime integration surface for debug overlays."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields-3","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields-3","type":"content","content":"- activateschedule: Interned<dyn ScheduleLabel> - deactivateschedule: Interned<dyn ScheduleLabel> - updateschedule: Interned<dyn ScheduleLabel> - debugsettings: HexGridDebugSettings"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Constructors","anchor":"#constructors","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Constructors","anchor":"#constructors","type":"content","content":"- HexGridPlugin::new(activate, deactivate, update) - HexGridPlugin::alwayson(update) - HexGridPlugin::default() which is equivalent to alwayson(Update) - withdebugsettings(HexGridDebugSettings)"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Scheduling guidance","anchor":"#scheduling-guidance","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Scheduling guidance","anchor":"#scheduling-guidance","type":"content","content":"- Use new(...) when the overlay should only exist inside a state-driven screen or tool mode. - Use alwayson(Update) or Default for examples, labs, and always-available editor tooling. - The plugin only draws when its runtime state is active. - The plugin initializes HexGridDebugGizmos for you, so callers do not need a separate initgizmo_group::<HexGridDebugGizmos>() step."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Traversal closure contracts","anchor":"#traversal-closure-contracts","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Traversal closure contracts","anchor":"#traversal-closure-contracts","type":"content","content":"The pathfinding functions are configured through closures rather than a config struct."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`a_star`","anchor":"#a-star","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`a_star`","anchor":"#a-star","type":"content","content":"Return: - None for blocked edges or out-of-bounds cells - Some(cost) for a legal move with positive cost"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`reachable_within`","anchor":"#reachable-within","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`reachable_within`","anchor":"#reachable-within","type":"content","content":"The same closure contract applies. Positive costs are required. Zero-cost edges are not supported."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Why closures are used","anchor":"#why-closures-are-used","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Why closures are used","anchor":"#why-closures-are-used","type":"content","content":"The closure-based design keeps storage and rule ownership outside the crate: - HashMap worlds - ECS queries - chunked map streams - tool-only procedural generators - directional terrain rules The crate only needs access to local traversal policy, not a fixed map container type."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Field of view closure contracts","anchor":"#field-of-view-closure-contracts","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`range_fov`","anchor":"#range-fov","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`range_fov`","anchor":"#range-fov","type":"content","content":"Return true if the hex blocks line of sight. Blocking hexes are included in the result (you can see a wall, but not past it). The origin is always included."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`directional_fov`","anchor":"#directional-fov","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`directional_fov`","anchor":"#directional-fov","type":"content","content":"Same blocking contract as range_fov, but restricted to a 120-degree cone facing the given HexDirection. The origin is always included."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexBounds`","anchor":"#hexbounds","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexBounds`","anchor":"#hexbounds","type":"content","content":"Circular bounds for hexagonal regions."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields-4","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields-4","type":"content","content":"- center: AxialHex - radius: u32"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Methods","anchor":"#methods","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Methods","anchor":"#methods","type":"content","content":"- new(center, radius) — construct bounds - contains(hex) — test membership - hex_count() — total cells in the region: 3R(R+1)+1 - iter() — iterate over all contained hexes - intersects(other) — test whether two bounds overlap - wrap(hex) — wrap a hex coordinate to stay within the bounds (modular wrapping)"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Guidance","anchor":"#guidance-1","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Guidance","anchor":"#guidance-1","type":"content","content":"- Use HexBounds for quick region containment checks without allocating a set - wrap is useful for toroidal or repeating maps - Implements IntoIterator for ergonomic for-loops"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexagonalMap<T>`","anchor":"#hexagonalmap-t","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`HexagonalMap<T>`","anchor":"#hexagonalmap-t","type":"content","content":"Dense O(1)-indexed storage over a hexagonal region, backed by a flat Vec<T>."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Constructors","anchor":"#constructors-1","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Constructors","anchor":"#constructors-1","type":"content","content":"- HexagonalMap::new(center, radius, -> T) — fill via closure - HexagonalMap::with_default(center, radius) — fill with T::default()"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Methods","anchor":"#methods-1","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Methods","anchor":"#methods-1","type":"content","content":"- center() — the center hex - radius() — the radius of the storage region - len() — total stored elements - isempty() — whether the map has no elements - contains(hex) — test if a hex is within the storage bounds - get(hex) -> Option<&T> — safe access - getmut(hex) -> Option<&mut T> — safe mutable access - iter() — iterate over (AxialHex, &T) pairs - iter_mut() — iterate over (AxialHex, &mut T) pairs"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Indexing","anchor":"#indexing","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Indexing","anchor":"#indexing","type":"content","content":"Supports Index<AxialHex> and IndexMut<AxialHex> for direct access. Panics on out-of-bounds access (use get/get_mut for fallible access)."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Guidance","anchor":"#guidance-2","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Guidance","anchor":"#guidance-2","type":"content","content":"- Prefer HexagonalMap over HashMap<AxialHex, T> when the region is known at construction time for better cache locality and O(1) access - iter() and iter_mut() follow the internal row-major order without allocating temporary coordinate buffers - The internal layout uses row-by-row flat indexing, so iteration order follows rows from bottom to top"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`GridEdge`","anchor":"#gridedge","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`GridEdge`","anchor":"#gridedge","type":"content","content":"Canonical edge between two adjacent hexes."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields-5","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields-5","type":"content","content":"- hex: AxialHex — the canonical hex (lexicographically smaller) - direction: HexDirection — the canonical direction"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Methods","anchor":"#methods-2","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Methods","anchor":"#methods-2","type":"content","content":"- new(hex, direction) — creates edge in canonical form - hexes() — the two hexes sharing this edge - vertices() — the two vertices at the endpoints of this edge"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Guidance","anchor":"#guidance-3","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Guidance","anchor":"#guidance-3","type":"content","content":"- Two GridEdge values are equal regardless of which side you construct from: GridEdge::new(a, East) == GridEdge::new(b, West) when b is east of a - Useful for strategy games with border features (rivers, walls, roads along hex edges)"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`GridVertex`","anchor":"#gridvertex","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"`GridVertex`","anchor":"#gridvertex","type":"content","content":"Canonical vertex shared by three adjacent hexes."},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields-6","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Fields","anchor":"#fields-6","type":"content","content":"- hex: AxialHex — the canonical hex (lexicographically smallest of the three) - direction: HexDiagonalDirection — the canonical diagonal direction"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Methods","anchor":"#methods-3","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Methods","anchor":"#methods-3","type":"content","content":"- new(hex, direction) — creates vertex in canonical form - hexes() — the three hexes sharing this vertex - edges() — the three edges meeting at this vertex"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Guidance","anchor":"#guidance-4","type":"heading","level":3},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Guidance","anchor":"#guidance-4","type":"content","content":"- Three GridVertex values are equal regardless of which hex you construct from - Useful for strategy games with vertex features (cities, intersections, resource nodes)"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Distance methods on `AxialHex`","anchor":"#distance-methods-on-axialhex","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Distance methods on `AxialHex`","anchor":"#distance-methods-on-axialhex","type":"content","content":"- distanceto(other) -> u32 — Manhattan (hex) distance - distancesqto(other) -> f32 — squared Euclidean distance (no sqrt, useful for comparisons and sorting) - euclideandistance_to(other) -> f32 — Euclidean distance between hex centers"},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Direction enhancements on `HexDirection`","anchor":"#direction-enhancements-on-hexdirection","type":"heading","level":2},{"title":"`saddle-world-hex-grid` Configuration","slug":"/docs/configuration/","heading":"Direction enhancements on `HexDirection`","anchor":"#direction-enhancements-on-hexdirection","type":"content","content":"- angle() -> f32 — direction angle in radians from positive x-axis - unitvector() -> Vec2 — unit vector pointing in this direction - vertexdirections() -> [HexDiagonalDirection; 2] — the two diagonal (vertex) directions adjacent to this face direction - from_angle(angle: f32) -> Self — nearest face direction to an arbitrary angle"}]');export{e as default};
